## The Latest Quarter At A Glance

Data on India's Gross Domestic Product for Quarter 3 of the 2024-25 fiscal year has just been published. Here are some highlights:

-   Inflation-adjusted Gross Domestic Product was INR 4,716,992.50 crores at constant 2011-12 prices. (A crore is ten million or 10<sup>7</sup>.)\
-   This represents a growth of [6.15 percent]{style="color: red;"} compared to the same quarter in the previous fiscal year. (The available quarterly data spans Quarter 1 of the 2011-12 fiscal year through Quarter 3 of the 2024-25 fiscal year. That's roughly 13 years. Over this period, GDP has grown [5.95 percent]{style="color: blue;"} annually.)
-   Consumption spending grew [6.91 percent]{style="color: red;"}. (Over the past 13 years, consumption spending has grown [6.33 percent]{style="color: blue;"} annually.)
-   Investment spending grew [4.99 percent]{style="color: red;"}. (Over the past 13 years, investment spending has grown [5.12 percent]{style="color: blue;"} annually.)
-   Government purchases grew [8.28 percent]{style="color: red;"}. (Over the past 13 years, government purchases has grown [4.15 percent]{style="color: blue;"} annually.)\
-   Exports grew [10.38 percent]{style="color: red;"}. (Over the past 13 years, exports has grown [4.99 percent]{style="color: blue;"} annually.)
-   Imports grew [-1.09 percent]{style="color: red;"}. (Over the past 13 years, imports has grown [3.04 percent]{style="color: blue;"} annually.)
-   Net Exports grew [90.46 percent]{style="color: red;"}. (Over the past 13 years, net exports has grown [5.18 percent]{style="color: blue;"} annually.)
-   Summary of the latest quarter: **It was slightly better than usual. GDP growth was slightly above the long-run average, as was growth in consumption spending. Government spending and exports were the main story: they both grew twice as fast as they usually do. Investment spending was a disappointment, growing slower than usual.**

